## Summary

When `gbrain serve --http --enable-dcr` is used, **every** OAuth `authorization_code` token exchange fails with `invalid_client / Invalid client_secret`, including for clients that just successfully registered via `/register` and immediately used the returned secret. Same affects `refresh_token` grant. This makes DCR-based MCP clients (Claude.ai, etc.) completely unable to connect.

## Root cause

Two interacting code paths:

1. **`src/core/oauth-provider.ts:145`** — `GBrainClientsStore.getClient()` returns the SHA-256 hash in the `client_secret` field:
   ```ts
   client_secret: r.client_secret_hash as string | undefined,
   ```

2. **`@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/././middleware/clientAuth.js:23`** does plain string compare.

The plaintext secret from the request can never `===` the SHA-256 hex digest returned by `getClient()`. 

## Workaround (one-line middleware patch)

```ts
app.post('/token', express.urlencoded({ extended: false }), (req, _res, next) => {
  const grant = req.body?.grant_type;
  if ((grant === 'authorization_code' || grant === 'refresh_token') && typeof req.body?.client_secret === 'string') {
    req.body.client_secret = createHash('sha256').update(req.body.client_secret).digest('hex');
  }
  next();
});
```

Verified against Claude.ai's connector flow. Happy to send a PR.

## Summary

Invoking `--help` on `gbrain sync` (and several other `CLI_ONLY` commands) triggers a live operation against the configured brain root instead of displaying help text. This is a structural CLI-dispatch bug: anyone exploring the CLI to understand `sync`'s behavior accidentally triggers a live sync.

## Repro (minimal, sandboxed)

```bash
export GBRAIN_HOME=/tmp/.gbrain-bug-repro
mkdir -p $GBRAIN_HOME && echo "# test" > $GBRAIN_HOME/test.md
gbrain sync --help
```

## Expected

Standard help output: usage, flags, examples. No side effects.

## Actual

Live sync executes against `$GBRAIN_HOME/`:
```
$ gbrain sync --help
Already up to date.
$ echo $?
0
```
No help text printed; sync ran and short-circuited at `up_to_date`. On a fresh / non-empty brain root this would consume embedding compute + wall-clock + DB writes.

## Affected version

gbrain 0.22.6 (`bun bin/gbrain --version`). Confirmed reproduces on local checkout + likely on `master` HEAD `3c032d79` (2026-05-03) — relevant code path unchanged.

## Other affected commands (matrix)

| Command | Class | `--help` behavior |
|---|---|---|
| `gbrain --help` | root | ✅ prints help |
| `gbrain query --help` | shared op (`cliOps`) | ✅ prints help via `printOpHelp(op)` |
| `gbrain embed --help` | `CLI_ONLY` | ✅ prints usage (own handler implements it) |
| `gbrain config --help` | `CLI_ONLY` | ✅ prints usage (own handler implements it) |
| **`gbrain sync --help`** | `CLI_ONLY` | 🐛 **fires live sync** |
| **`gbrain doctor --help`** | `CLI_ONLY` | 🐛 **runs full doctor diagnostic suite** |

The bug affects `CLI_ONLY` commands that don't implement their own `--help` short-circuit in their handler. `sync` and `doctor` are confirmed; the other ~40 entries in `CLI_ONLY` (`autopilot`, `eval`, `agent`, `migrate`, `extract`, `dream`, `serve`, `import`, `export`, ...) likely fall in the same category unless individually audited.

## Root cause (`src/cli.ts` lines 57-70)

```typescript
// Per-command --help
if (subArgs.includes('--help') || subArgs.includes('-h')) {
  const op = cliOps.get(command);
  if (op) {
    printOpHelp(op);
    return;
  }
}

// CLI-only commands
if (CLI_ONLY.has(command)) {
  await handleCliOnly(command, subArgs);
  return;
}
```

The per-command `--help` short-circuit only fires when `cliOps.get(command)` returns a shared op. For `CLI_ONLY` commands (`sync`, `doctor`, ...), `cliOps.get()` returns `undefined`, so the `if (op)` branch never executes and dispatch falls through to `handleCliOnly()`, which forwards `--help` as a regular arg to the command's own handler. Commands whose handler doesn't itself parse `--help` proceed to do their default work.

## Severity

Medium. The operation is idempotent and re-syncs already-indexed content cheaply on a warm cache. **But:**
- First-time CLI explorers accidentally trigger a live sync against their real brain root.
- On a misconfigured `GBRAIN_HOME` pointing at a sensitive folder, side effects are more serious.
- `gbrain doctor --help` runs the full doctor suite (DB checks, file walks, embedding sanity, brain_score recompute) — non-trivial wall-clock.
- Violates the principle of least surprise; `--help` should be inert in any well-behaved CLI.

## Suggested fix

Add a `CLI_ONLY` branch to the per-command `--help` short-circuit so help is handled at the dispatcher level rather than relying on each handler:

```typescript
if (subArgs.includes('--help') || subArgs.includes('-h')) {
  const op = cliOps.get(command);
  if (op) {
    printOpHelp(op);
    return;
  }
  if (CLI_ONLY.has(command)) {
    // Print a CLI_ONLY help registry entry, or invoke a `printCliOnlyHelp(command)` lookup.
    printCliOnlyHelp(command);
    return;
  }
}
```

Alternative: refactor every `CLI_ONLY` command to short-circuit on `--help` at the top of its own handler (more places to change, easier to forget; the dispatcher-level fix is uniform).

## Repro environment

- macOS 26.4.1 (Build 25E253)
- bun 1.3.13
- LM Studio on `localhost:1234` (Path B configuration; `OPENAI_BASE_URL` redirect)
- gbrain 0.22.6 / commit `be8fffad`
